%^^A % How we organize our data will of course influence the
%^^A % performance of the algorithm. Let us denote by $n$ the
%^^A % size of the NFA and $L$ the length of the string. The
%^^A % number of threads $t$ is always less than or equal to $n$,
%^^A % and changes at each step. The number $g$ of capturing groups
%^^A % is also less than $n$, and often much smaller.
%^^A %
%^^A % The NFA must be stored either in \cs{toks} registers
%^^A % (access in $O(1)$), or in a property list (access in $O(n)$).
%^^A % We have the same alternative for submatches, either
%^^A % toks in $O(g)$ or property list in $O(gt)$.
%^^A %
%^^A % For each character in the string, we loop over the chained list
%^^A % of threads. For each of those threads, we read the corresponding
%^^A % instruction of the program. If this is a \enquote{split}
%^^A % instruction, copies of the current thread are created and inserted
%^^A % in the chained list. Submatches found so far are also copied (maybe?).
%^^A % If this is a character instruction, the current character is tested,
%^^A % and if it matches, we move the thread to the next instruction in
%^^A % the program.
%^^A %
%^^A % Three main costs: looking up the program instruction,
%^^A % storing submatch information, and killing a thread
%^^A % (removing its submatch information is the slow bit).
%^^A %
%^^A % All the times below are wrong: I forgot the time to kill a thread
%^^A % and remove its submatch info. Let $l$ be the typical life-span
%^^A % of a thread. Then at each char $t/l$ threads die. Similarly, at
%^^A % each char, $gt/n$ threads require us to store submatch information,
%^^A % and the total amount of submatch information is $gt$.
%^^A % \begin{itemize}
%^^A % \item NFA as toks, submatches as prop.
%^^A %   Looking up the NFA costs $Lt$ in total.
%^^A %   Submatches storage costs $Lg^2t^2/n$.
%^^A %   Killing costs $Lgt^2/l$.
%^^A %   Copying costs $Lgt$.
%^^A % \item NFA as prop, submatches as toks.
%^^A %   [Impossible! the number of threads is unbounded.]
%^^A %   ^^A Looking up the NFA costs $Lnt$.
%^^A %   ^^A Submatches storage costs $Lg^2t/n$
%^^A %   ^^A Killing costs $Lgt/l$.
%^^A %   ^^A Copying costs $Lgt/l$.
%^^A % \item NFA as toks, submatches as toks, threadwise.
%^^A %   [Impossible! the number of threads is unbounded.]
%^^A %   ^^A Looking up the NFA costs $Lgt$.
%^^A %   ^^A Submatches storage costs $Lg^2t/n$
%^^A %   ^^A Killing costs $Lgt/l$
%^^A %   ^^A Copying costs $Lgt/l$
%^^A % \item NFA as toks, submatches at the corresponding program instruction.
%^^A %   Looking up the NFA costs $Lt$.
%^^A %   Submatches storage costs $Lgt^2/n$.
%^^A %   Killing costs $Lgt^2/l$.
%^^A %   Copying costs $Lgt^2/l$.
%^^A % \end{itemize}
%^^A % It looks as if the last one might be a faster option than the first,
%^^A % but it also looks quite messy, and requires to keep track of another
%^^A % list for each thread, so things are not too clear.
%^^A %
%^^A % I'll go for the first method, storing program instructions
%^^A % in \TeX{}'s toks registers, and submatch information
%^^A % in a property list. To each program instruction is associated:
%^^A % \begin{itemize}
%^^A % \item the thread number,
%^^A % \item the program instruction at which
%^^A %   the next thread in the chained list is.
%^^A % \end{itemize}
%^^A % This information is stored as the normal and stretch components
%^^A % of a \cs{skip} or \cs{muskip} register (alternating depending
%^^A % on the step).
